ized to `git reset --hard`**\\n\\n`/Users/pfleidi/entire/cli/cmd/entire/cli/rewind.go` lines 1142-1148:\\n```go\\nfunc performGitResetHard(commitHash string) error {\\n    ctx := context.Background()\\n    cmd := exec.CommandContext(ctx, \\\"git\\\", \\\"reset\\\", \\\"--hard\\\", commitHash)\\n    ...\\n```\\n\\nCalled at lines 614 and 1010 with `point.ID`. The `RewindPoint.ID` field (`strategy/strategy.go` line 75) is a free-form string - it can be a commit hash, a branch name, or a stash ref. The `FetchAndCheckoutRemoteBranch` function validates branch names with `git check-ref-format` before passing them to `exec.Command`, but `performGitResetHard` has no equivalent guard. If `point.ID` were ever populated with something like `-q --mixed` or a path starting with `--`, git would misinterpret the arguments. Since `RewindPoint` values come from internal checkpoint metadata (not direct user string input), the exploitability is low, but the function should add `--` before the hash:\\n```go\\ncmd := exec.CommandContext(ctx, \\\"git\\\", \\\"reset\\\", \\\"--hard\\\", \\\"--\\\", commitHash)\\n```\\nThe same applies to `CheckoutBranch` at `/Users/pfleidi/entire/cli/cmd/entire/cli/git_operations.go` line 295:\\n```go\\ncmd := exec.CommandContext(ctx, \\\"git\\\", \\\"checkout\\\", ref)\\n```\\nThis function is called with `point.ID` from `rewind.go:909`. Using `git checkout --` would prevent any argument injection.\\n\\n**`PAGER` environment variable passed directly to `exec.Command`**\\n\\n`/Users/pfleidi/entire/cli/cmd/entire/cli/explain.go` lines 1280-1285:\\n```go\\npager := os.Getenv(\\\"PAGER\\\")\\nif pager == \\\"\\\" {\\n    pager = \\\"less\\\"\\n}\\ncmd := exec.CommandContext(context.Background(), pager) //nolint:gosec // pager from env is expected\\n```\\nIf `PAGER` is set to a path like `/tmp/evil` or an executable that doesn't exist, it will either fail gracefully (fallback to `fmt.Fprint`) or execute an arbitrary binary. The `//nolint:gosec` suppression is appropriate for the subprocess spawning warning, but there is no validation that `pager` is an absolute path, does not contain spaces/arguments, or is one of a known-safe set. Since `PAGER` is user-controlled and the fallback on error is benign, the real risk is limited to self-inflicted problems. However, consider using `exec.LookPath(pager)` to validate existence before running, or explicitly splitting on spaces to handle `PAGER=less -R`.\\n\\n**`spawnDetachedAnalytics` passes JSON payload as a command-line argument**\\n\\n`/Users/pfleidi/entire/cli/cmd/entire/cli/telemetry/detached_unix.go` line 23:\\n```go\\ncmd := exec.CommandContext(context.Background(), executable, \\\"__send_analytics\\\", payloadJSON)\\n```\\n`payloadJSON` is a JSON-serialized struct containing `machine_id`, `command_path`, `strategy`, `agent`, `version`, `os`, `arch`, and `flags` (flag names only, not values). No user-provided free-form strings with sensitive content go into this payload. The comment at `detached.go` line 25 correctly notes the API key is not passed this way. This is low-risk, and the `nolint:gosec` annotation is well-justified.\\n\\n**`PostHogAPIKey` default value is `\\\"phc_development_key\\\"` in source**\\n\\n`/Users/pfleidi/entire/cli/cmd/entire/cli/telemetry/detached.go` line 18:\\n```go\\nPostHogAPIKey = \\\"phc_development_key\\\"\\n```\\nThis is intentional - the real key is injected at build time via ldflags in `.goreleaser.yaml` line 23. Development builds use the placeholder, which would produce invalid telemetry calls. This is fine by design, but worth documenting clearly (a `//nolint:gosec` or comment about the ldflags injection would help since gosec or secret-scanning tools may flag it as a low-entropy key literal).\\n\\n**Test files contain a high-entropy string resembling an Anthropic key**\\n\\n`/Users/pfleidi/entire/cli/redact/redact_test.go` line 10 and `/Users/pfleidi/entire/cli/cmd/entire/cli/checkpoint/checkpoint_test.go` line 2695:\\n```go\\ncon